        "narrative_summary": "The BRCA2 c.1141G>A (p.Asp381Asn) missense change occurs in the DNA‑repair gene BRCA2, a locus implicated in hereditary breast and ovarian cancer susceptibility. In a large‑scale ENIGMA multifactorial likelihood analysis the variant was assigned a combined likelihood ratio that favoured a benign interpretation and was classified as likely benign, although ClinVar entries for the same change include conflicting interpretations such as uncertain significance [PMC6772163]. No functional assays or experimental studies of the variant were reported in the extracted literature, so functional evidence is lacking [PMC6617753][PMC6282857]. Population data from the ENIGMA study indicate that the allele is observed at a frequency of at least 0.0001 but less than 0.01 in Latino cohorts, a range that the authors consider strong evidence supporting benignity; no additional computational predictions were provided [PMC6772163]. Taken together, the preponderance of evidence points toward a benign or likely benign status for BRCA2 c.1141G>A, with the caveat that some clinical databases still list it as of uncertain significance, reflecting residual uncertainty in its classification.",
        "structured_summary": {
            "overall_pathogenicity": "benign",
